      <title>Dropbox looks beyond the cloud with email, photo apps, better business features</title>
      <pubDate>Wed, 09 Apr 2014 12:24:00 -0700</pubDate>
      <author>Brad Chacos</author>
      <dc:creator>Brad Chacos</dc:creator>
      <description><![CDATA[<article>
	<section class="page">
<p>
Dropbox shook up its service on Wednesday, announcing a slew of updates and new services designed for work and play alike. Amidst the flurry of announcements, one thing became startlingly clear: Google Drive may have the cheapest consumer cloud prices around, but Dropbox wants to be more than just a simple storage locker.</p><h2>Of Mailboxes and Carousels</h2>
<p>
After innovative email app Mailbox <a href="http://www.macworld.com/article/2027388/review-mailbox-for-iphone-belongs-in-your-dock.html">won the hearts of iPhone users</a> in February of last year, Dropbox gobbled it up in March.</p><figure class="large "><a class="zoom" href="https://cms-images.idgesg.net/images/article/2014/04/mailbox-android-100260221-orig.png"><img src="https://cms-images.idgesg.net/images/article/2014/04/mailbox-android-100260221-large.png" alt="mailbox android" width="580" height="192"/></a> <figcaption>
<p>
Mailbox is officially on Android now and already available in the Play Store.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/2141820/dropbox-looks-beyond-the-cloud-with-new-apps-and-dropbox-for-business-roll-out.html#jump">To read this article in full or to leave a comment, please click here</a></p></section></article>]]></description>
