      <title>Intel and SGI cool servers by dunking them</title>
      <pubDate>Tue, 08 Apr 2014 15:52:00 -0700</pubDate>
      <author>Agam Shah</author>
      <dc:creator>Agam Shah</dc:creator>
      <description><![CDATA[<article>
	<section class="page">
<p>
Intel and SGI have been testing a supercomputer that’s kept cool by submerging the electronics completely in fluid, a system they say can dramatically reduce energy bills.</p><p>
The companies built a proof-of-concept supercomputer that’s kept cool using a fluid developed by 3M called Novec. It’s a dielectric liquid, which means electronics can be submerged in it and continue to operate normally.</p><p>
Novec is already used in fire suppression systems, and Intel and SGI are now testing its viability as a more efficient cooling system for computers, where they say it could replace fans and eliminate the need to use tons of municipal water to cool data centers.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/2141500/intel-and-sgi-test-fullimmersion-cooling-for-servers.html#jump">To read this article in full or to leave a comment, please click here</a></p></section></article>]]></description>
